         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve"><head>Translations</head>
            <div type="translation" source="#jmr-jbwp-rgg2003" xml:lang="en"><p><note>Perhaps a reference to Abraham</note></p></div>
            </div>
       
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>For the building, probably of the sixth century, see Ward-Perkins, op. cit, 326-341</p>
            <p> The name Abraham is clear. Τhe formula 'in the bosom of Abraham', ἐν κόλπῳ/κόλποις Ἀβρααμ  is usually found in a funerary context; but the protection of the God of Abraham 
               is sometimes invoked: so from Egyptian Thebes <title>SEG</title> 8,754 κ(υρι)ε θ(εο)ς Ἀβραὰμ καὶ Ἰσαὰκ καὶ Ἰακὼβ  (available at <title>PHI</title> <ref target="https://epigraphy.packhum.org/text/223145">223145</ref>) 
               and SEG 8,740, (available at <title>PHI</title> <ref target="https://epigraphy.packhum.org/text/223131">223131</ref>). 
               For a private invocation cf. <title>SEG</title> 8,240  Ἅγιε Ἀβράαμα βωήθεν τὸν δοῦλόν σου, from Hebron, the site of Abraham's tomb 
               (available at <title>PHI</title> <ref target="https://epigraphy.packhum.org/text/319482">319482</ref>). <!-- For Abraham in Christian inscriptions cf. Cabrol Leclerq s.v., and Reallex. f. Antike und Christentum, s.v. -->. But this could also be a personal name.</p>
         </div>
         
